# Public copy: no long dashes

When editing or generating content for websites, HTML, components that render to the page, or anything user-visible:

- Do **not** use the em dash (U+2014) or en dash (U+2013) in copy, headings, buttons, labels, placeholders, `title` / `alt` text, meta descriptions, or visible strings in code.
- Use plain ASCII instead: hyphen-minus `-`, commas, parentheses, colons, or rephrase the sentence.

Examples:

```html
<!-- BAD -->
<p>We ship fast—without cutting corners.</p>

<!-- GOOD -->
<p>We ship fast, without cutting corners.</p>
<p>We ship fast (without cutting corners).</p>
```

```html
<!-- BAD: en dash in ranges in visible text can be written for humans as "to" or hyphen -->
<p>Berlin–Munich in 4 hours</p>

<!-- GOOD -->
<p>Berlin to Munich in 4 hours</p>
```

This does not forbid minus signs in math or code logic; it targets **typographic** dashes in **public-facing text**.
